# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1923-boston-red-sox-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1901-boston-americans-season] The **1901 Boston Americans season** was the first season for the professional baseball franchise that later became known as the Boston Red Sox, and the first season of play for the American League (AL).
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1901-boston-americans-season] It resulted in the Americans finishing second in the AL with a record of 79 wins and 57 losses, four games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1901-boston-americans-season] The team was managed by Jimmy Collins and played its home games at Huntington Avenue Grounds.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1901-boston-americans-season] On February 11, Jimmy Collins, third baseman for the National League Boston Beaneaters became the first player under contract for the Boston Americans after being offered a contract of $4000 with the added ability to sign subsequent players to contracts.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Collins was joined on March 4 by the outfielder Chick Stahl, who was also from the Beaneaters.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Defecting with Stahl and Collins was the outfielder Buck Freeman.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Yet perhaps the most important signing was that of the 34 year old St.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Louis Cardinals pitcher Cy Young, who accepted a contract worth $3500 from the Boston Americans.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Vital to the signing of Cy Young from the Cardinals was the signing of Cy Young's catcher in St.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Louis, Lou Criger; the value that Young gave to Criger and that Criger gave to Young was so strong, that it is unlikely that Young would have signed for the Americans if Criger had not done so.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Prior to the regular season, the team held spring training in Charlottesville, Virginia.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1901-boston-americans-season] The total attendance for the Red Sox was 289,448, the second most in the American League (behind the White Sox' 354,350) and more than the crosstown Boston Beaneaters' 146,502.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1901-boston-americans-season] The offense was led by Buck Freeman, who hit 12 home runs and had 114 RBIs while recording a .339 batting average.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1901-boston-americans-season] The pitching staff was led by Cy Young, who made 43 appearances (41 starts) and pitched 38 complete games with a 33–10 record and 1.62 ERA, while striking out 158 in 371+1⁄3 innings.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1901-boston-americans-season] The team had two games end in a tie; August 31 at Detroit Tigers and September 12 at Washington Senators.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Tied games are not counted in league standings, but player statistics during tied games are counted.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Cy Young led the league in ERA (1.62), shutouts (5; tied with Clark Griffith), strikeouts (158), and wins (33).
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The **1901 major league baseball season** was contested from April 18 through October 6, 1901.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] It was the inaugural major league season for the American League (AL) (having previously been the minor league Western League), with the Chicago White Stockings winning the AL pennant.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] In the National League (NL), in operation since 1876, the Pittsburgh Pirates won the NL pennant.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first season of the modern era.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This would be the only season in which the Milwaukee Brewers played, as the team would relocate to St.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Louis, Missouri for the following season as the St.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns (before that team relocated to Baltimore, Maryland as the modern Baltimore Orioles in 1954, where they remain to this day.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The Baltimore Orioles of this season would fold following the 1902 season).
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The 1901 schedule consisted of 140 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 20 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This format had previously been used by the National League during their 1888–1891 seasons.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This format would last until 1904, which saw an increase of games played.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on April 18 with a game between the Brooklyn Superbas and the Philadelphia Phillies, while American League Opening Day did not take place until April 24, with a game between the Chicago White Stockings and the Cleveland Bluebirds.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The American League would see its final day of the season on September 28, while the National League would see its final day of the season on October 6.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] On February 27, 1901, the National League Rules Committee announced several rule changes, effective immediately.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Blue laws restricted Sunday activities in several localities, causing several teams to play at ballparks in a different locality.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] 15 tie games (8 in AL, 7 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Reds would play their final game at League Park, on October 6 during a doubleheader against the St.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals, moving into the Palace of the Fans for the start of the 1902 season.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1902-boston-americans-season] The **1902 Boston Americans season** was the second season for the professional baseball franchise that later became known as the Boston Red Sox.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1902-boston-americans-season] The Americans finished third in the American League (AL) with a record of 77 wins and 60 losses, 6+1⁄2 games behind the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1902-boston-americans-season] The Americans bolstered their pitching by recruiting Bill Dinneen, who jumped from the Boston Beaneaters.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1902-boston-americans-season] Dinneen and Cy Young would become the "one-two" pitching combination for the Boston Americans.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1902-boston-americans-season] Prior to the regular season, the team held spring training in Augusta, Georgia.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1902-boston-americans-season] The offense was led by Buck Freeman, who hit 11 home runs and had 121 RBIs, and Patsy Dougherty with a .342 batting average.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1902-boston-americans-season] The pitching staff was led by Cy Young, who made 45 appearances (43 starts) and pitched 41 complete games with a 32–11 record and 2.15 ERA, while striking out 160 in 384+2⁄3 innings.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1902-boston-americans-season] The team had one game end in a tie; August 18 vs.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1902-boston-americans-season] Tie games are not counted in league standings, but player statistics during tie games are counted.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The **1903 Boston Americans season** was the third season for the professional baseball franchise that later became known as the Boston Red Sox.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Americans finished first in the American League (AL) with a record of 91 wins and 47 losses, 14+1⁄2 games ahead of the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Boston went on to participate in the first World Series held between the AL and National League (NL) champions.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Americans won the 1903 World Series in eight games over the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Prior to the regular season, the team held spring training in Macon, Georgia.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Cy Young was a coach for the Mercer University baseball team, also based in Macon.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Boston Americans played an exhibition game against Mercer University (with Cy Young pitching for Mercer) on March 23; the outcome being a 13─2 victory for Boston.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team's longest losing streak was three games, which occurred twice; April 20–23 and September 22–23.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team's longest game was 12 innings, which occurred three times.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The offense was led by Buck Freeman, who hit 13 home runs and had 104 RBIs, and Patsy Dougherty with a .331 batting average.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-boston-americans-season] It was Freeman's third consecutive season with at least 100 RBIs.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The pitching staff was led by Cy Young, who made 40 appearances (35 starts) and pitched 34 complete games with a 28–9 record and 2.08 ERA, while striking out 176 in 341+2⁄3 innings.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team had two other 20-game winners; Bill Dinneen (21–13) and Tom Hughes (20–7).
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team had three games end in a tie; July 31 at Washington, August 29 at Washington, and September 25 vs.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Boston had an 11-game winning streak from May 28 through June 8, to put themselves in the AL lead.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-boston-americans-season] While they briefly fell into second place in mid-June, behind Philadelphia, Boston then won 9-of-10 to recapture the lead, which they held through the end of the season.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Americans met the Pittsburgh Pirates in the first modern World Series, an agreement between the AL and the NL as a post-season tournament.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The "Amerks" won the best-of-nine series in eight games; after falling behind, 3–1, they won four games in a row, clinching the championship at their home field, the Huntington Avenue Grounds, in Boston.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] The **1903 World Series** was the first modern World Series to be played in Major League Baseball.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] It matched the American League (AL) champion Boston Americans (now the Boston Red Sox) against the National League (NL) champion Pittsburgh Pirates in a best-of-nine series, with Boston prevailing five games to three, winning the last four.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] This was the first major professional sports championship ever won by a Boston-based team.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] The first three games were played in Boston, the next four in Allegheny (home of the Pirates), and the eighth (last) game in Boston.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] Pittsburgh pitcher Sam Leever injured his shoulder while trap shooting, so his teammate Deacon Phillippe pitched five complete games.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] Phillippe won three of his games, but it was not enough to overcome the club from the new American League.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] Boston pitchers Bill Dinneen and Cy Young led Boston to victory.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] In Game 1, Phillippe struck out ten Boston batters.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] The next day, Dinneen bettered that mark, striking out 11 Pittsburgh batters in Game 2.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] Honus Wagner, bothered by injuries, batted only 6-for-27 (.222) in the Series and committed six errors.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] The shortstop was deeply distraught by his performance.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] The following spring, Wagner (who in 1903 led the National League in batting average) refused to send his portrait to a "Hall of Fame" for batting champions.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] "I was a joke in that Boston-Pittsburgh Series.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] What does it profit a man to hammer along and make a few hits when they are not needed only to fall down when it comes to a pinch?
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] Due to overflow crowds at the Exposition Park games in Allegheny City, if a batted ball rolled under a rope in the outfield that held spectators back, a "ground-rule triple" would be scored.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] 17 ground-rule triples were hit in the four games played at the stadium.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] In the series, Boston came back from a three games to one deficit, winning the final four games to capture the title.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] Such a large comeback would not happen again until the Pirates came back to defeat the Washington Senators in the 1925 World Series, and has happened only 11 times in baseball history.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] (The Pirates themselves repeated this feat in 1979 against the Baltimore Orioles.) Much was made of the influence of Boston's "Royal Rooters", who traveled to Exposition Park and sang their theme song "Tessie" to distract the opposing players (especially Wagner).
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] Boston wound up winning three out of four games in Allegheny City.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] Pirates owner Barney Dreyfuss added his share of the gate receipts to the players' share, so the losing team's players actually finished with a larger individual share than the winning team's.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] The Series brought the new American League prestige and proved its best could beat the best of the National League, thus strengthening the demand for future World Series competitions.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] In 1901, Ban Johnson, president of the Western League, a minor league organization, formed the American League to take advantage of the National League's 1900 contraction from twelve teams to eight.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] Johnson and fellow owners raided the National League and signed away many star players, including Cy Young and Jimmy Collins.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] Johnson had a list of 46 National Leaguers he targeted for the American League; by 1902, all but one had made the jump.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] The constant raiding, however, nixed the idea of a championship between the two leagues.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] Pirates owner Barney Dreyfuss, whose team ran away with the 1902 National League pennant, was open to a postseason contest and even said he would allow the American League champion to stock its roster with all-stars.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] However, Johnson had spoken of putting a team in Pittsburgh and even attempted to raid the Pirates' roster in August 1902, which soured Dreyfuss.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] At the end of the season, however, the Pirates played a group of American League All-Stars in a four-game exhibition series, winning two games to one, with one tie.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] The leagues finally called a truce in the winter of 1902–03 and formed the National Commission to preside over organized baseball.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] The following season, the Boston Americans and Pittsburgh Pirates had secured their respective championship pennants by September.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] That August, Dreyfuss challenged the American League to an 11-game championship series.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] Encouraged by Johnson and National League President Harry Pulliam, Americans owner Henry J.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] Killilea met with Dreyfuss in Pittsburgh in September and instead agreed to a best-of-nine championship, with the first three games played in Boston, the next four in Allegheny City, and the remaining two (if necessary) in Boston.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] One significant point about this agreement was that it was an arrangement primarily between the two clubs rather than a formal arrangement between the leagues.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] In short, it was a voluntary event, a fact which would result in no Series at all for 1904.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] The formal establishment of the Series as a compulsory event started in 1905.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] The Pirates won their third straight pennant in 1903 thanks to a powerful lineup that included legendary shortstop Honus Wagner, who hit .355 and drove in 101 runs, player-manager Fred Clarke, who hit .351, and Ginger Beaumont, who hit .341 and led the league in hits and runs.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] The Pirates' pitching was weaker than it had been in previous years but boasted 24-game winner Deacon Phillippe and 25-game winner Sam Leever.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] The Americans had a strong pitching staff, led by Cy Young, who went 28–9 in 1903 and became the all-time wins leader that year.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] Bill Dinneen and Long Tom Hughes, right-handers like Young, had won 21 games and 20 games each.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] The Boston outfield, featuring Chick Stahl (.274), Buck Freeman (.287, 104 RBI) and Patsy Dougherty (.331, 101 runs scored) was considered excellent.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] Although the Pirates had dominated their league for the previous three years, they went into the series riddled with injuries and plagued by bizarre misfortunes.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] Otto Krueger, the team's only utility player, was beaned on September 19 and never fully played in the series.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] 16-game winner Ed Doheny left the team three days later, exhibiting signs of paranoia; he was committed to an insane asylum the following month.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] Leever had been battling an injury to his pitching arm (which he made worse by entering a trapshooting competition).
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] Worst of all, Wagner, who had a sore thumb throughout the season, injured his right leg in September and was never 100 percent for the postseason.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] Some sources say Boston were heavy underdogs.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] Boston bookies actually gave even odds to the teams (and only because Dreyfuss and other "sports" were alleged to have bet on Pittsburgh to bring down the odds).
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] The teams were generally thought to be evenly matched, with the Americans credited with stronger pitching and the Pirates with superior offense and fielding.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] The outcome, many believed, hinged on Wagner's health.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] The Pirates started Game 1 strong, scoring six runs in the first four innings, and held on to win the first World Series game in modern baseball history.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] They extended their lead to 7–0 on an inside-the-park home run by Jimmy Sebring in the seventh, the first home run in World Series history.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] Boston scored a few runs in the last three innings, but it was too little, too late; they ended up losing 7–3 in the first ever World Series game.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] Both Phillippe and Young threw complete games, with Phillippe striking out ten and Young fanning five, but Young also gave up twice as many hits and allowed three earned runs to Phillippe's two.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] After starting out strong in Game 1, the Pirates simply shut down offensively, eking out a mere three hits, all singles.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] Pittsburgh starter Sam Leever went 1 inning and gave up three hits and two runs, before his ailing arm forced him to leave in favor of Bucky Veil, who finished the game.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] Bill Dinneen struck out 11 and pitched a complete game for the Americans, while Patsy Dougherty hit home runs in the first and sixth innings for two of the Boston's three runs.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] The Americans' Patsy Dougherty led off the Boston scoring with an inside-the-park home run, the first time a lead-off batter did just that until Alcides Escobar of the Kansas City Royals duplicated the feat in the 2015 World Series, 112 years later.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] Dougherty's second home run was the first in World Series history to actually sail over the fence, an incredibly rare feat at the time.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] Phillippe, pitching after only a single day of rest, started Game 3 for the Pirates and didn't let them down, hurling his second complete-game victory of the Series to put Pittsburgh up two games to one.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] After two days of rest, Phillippe was ready to pitch a second straight game.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] He threw his third complete-game victory of the series against Bill Dinneen, who was making his second start of the series.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] But Phillippe's second straight win was almost not to be, as the Americans, down 5–1 in the top of the ninth, rallied to narrow the deficit to one run.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] The comeback attempt failed, as Phillippe managed to put an end to it and give the Pirates a commanding 3–1 series lead.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] Game 5 was a pitcher's duel for the first five innings, with Boston's Cy Young and Pittsburgh's Brickyard Kennedy giving up no runs.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] That changed in the top of the sixth, however, when the Americans scored a then-record six runs before being retired.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] Young, on the other hand, managed to keep his shutout intact before finally giving up a pair of runs in the bottom of the eighth.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] He went the distance and struck out four for his first World Series win.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] Game 6 was a rematch between the starters of Game 2, Boston's Dinneen and Pittsburgh's Leever.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] Leever pitched a complete game this time but so did Dinneen, who outmatched him to earn his second complete-game victory of the series.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] After losing three of the first four games of the World Series, the underdog Americans had tied the series at three games apiece.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] The fourth and final game in Allegheny saw Phillippe start his fourth game of the Series for the Pirates.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] This time, however, he did not fare as well as he did in his first three starts.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] Cy Young, in his third start of the Series, held the Pirates to three runs and put the Americans ahead for the first time as the Series moved back to Boston.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] The final game of this inaugural World Series started out as an intense pitcher's duel, scoreless until the bottom of the fourth when Hobe Ferris hit a two-run single.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] Phillippe started his fifth and final game of the series and Dinneen his fourth.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] The Red Sox would go on to be one of the most dominant teams of the early 20th century, winning four championships in six years during the 1910s decade.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] They would start their dynasty in 1912 when they won their next championship over the New York Giants in seven games.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1903-world-series] The Pirates would return to the World Series in 1909, and defeated the Detroit Tigers in seven games to win their first championship.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1904-boston-americans-season] The **1904 Boston Americans season** was the fourth season for the professional baseball franchise that later became known as the Boston Red Sox.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1904-boston-americans-season] The Americans finished first in the American League (AL) with a record of 95 wins and 59 losses, 1+1⁄2 games ahead of the New York Highlanders.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1904-boston-americans-season] The Americans were set to play the National League (NL) champion New York Giants in the 1904 World Series; however, the Giants refused to play.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1904-boston-americans-season] The offense was led by Buck Freeman, who hit 7 home runs and had 84 RBIs, and Freddy Parent with a .291 batting average.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1904-boston-americans-season] The pitching staff was led by Cy Young, who made 43 appearances (41 starts) and pitched 40 complete games with a 26–16 record and 1.97 ERA, while striking out 200 in 380 innings.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1904-boston-americans-season] The team had two other 20-game winners; Bill Dinneen (23–14) and Jesse Tannehill (21–11).
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1904-boston-americans-season] The team had three games end in a tie; September 13 at Philadelphia, September 14 vs.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1904-boston-americans-season] Both ties against New York were the second games of doubleheaders.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1904-boston-americans-season] Note: Stats in brackets are derived from Retrosheet which differ from the stats found on MLB.com.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1905-boston-americans-season] The **1905 Boston Americans season** was the fifth season for the professional baseball franchise that later became known as the Boston Red Sox.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1905-boston-americans-season] The Americans finished fourth in the American League (AL) with a record of 78 wins and 74 losses, 16 games behind the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1905-boston-americans-season] The offense was led by Jimmy Collins with 65 RBIs and a .276 batting average, and Hobe Ferris with six home runs.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1905-boston-americans-season] The team had one game end in a tie; June 22 vs.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1923-boston-red-sox-season] The **1923 Boston Red Sox season** was the 23rd season in the franchise's Major League Baseball history.
[src:1923-boston-red-sox-season/1923-boston-red-sox-season] The Red Sox finished last in the eight-team American League (AL) with a record of 61 wins and 91 losses, 37 games behind the New York Yankees, who went on to win the 1923 World Series.
